---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About — Huw Hallam"
  description="Data scientist with a background in art and music. Building civic technology, thinking about AI safety, and asking what data can do for society."
>
  <article class="about-page container">

    <div class="about-hero">
      <img
        src="/profile_image.jpg"
        alt="Huw Hallam"
        class="about-photo"
        width="260"
        height="260"
      />
      <div class="about-intro">
        <h1 class="hand">Not your average data scientist</h1>
        <p>
          Perhaps because I have a background in music and art, I tend to think about data
          as a listening and design problem. Before reaching for an algorithm, I'm asking:
          what is this data actually saying? What matters here, and to whom? I'm listening
          for signal in the noise, designing a way to communicate or build with it. I care
          as much about how an insight lands as whether it's technically correct.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      What motivates me most is the belief that data and AI can be genuinely useful for
      society — not just for optimising conversion rates. I'm drawn to the hard questions:
      how do we develop AI in ways that are safe and broadly beneficial? What would an
      economics of abundance actually look like? I write about these in
      <a href="/abundance"><em>Towards Abundance</em></a> — thinking out loud, in public,
      about what a good outcome might require.
    </p>

    <p>
      I'm also building <a href="/commons"><em>The Commons</em></a> — a civic platform
      aimed at reducing political polarisation and encouraging engagement in
      non-confrontational ways. I'm convinced that the tools of data science and AI,
      applied thoughtfully, could do real work here: helping people find common ground,
      understand different perspectives, and participate in public life without it feeling
      like a fight. I'm documenting the build as I go.
    </p>

    <p>
      An art and music background trains you to look at the world creatively — to imagine
      how things might be built differently, to see the gap between what exists and what
      could exist. That's the lens I bring to all of this.
    </p>

    <div class="about-links">
      <h2 class="hand">Elsewhere</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="https://huwhallam.github.io/portfolio/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Data science portfolio →
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://independent.academia.edu/HuwHallam" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Academia.edu →
          </a>
          <span class="link-note">
            Writing from a previous life as a music and contemporary art researcher
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .about-page {
    padding-block: 3rem 4rem;
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .about-hero {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    margin-bottom: 1.75rem;
  }

  .about-photo {
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 1;
    object-fit: cover;
    border-radius: 50%;
    border: 3px solid var(--bg-card);
    outline: 2px solid var(--accent);
    outline-offset: 3px;
  }

  .about-intro h1 {
    margin-bottom: 0.6em;
  }

  .about-intro p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .about-page > p {
    margin-bottom: 1.25em;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .about-links {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    border-top: 2px solid var(--bg-card);
  }

  .about-links h2 {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .about-links ul {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.6rem;
  }

  .about-links li {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .link-note {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--ink-light);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  @media (max-width: 540px) {
    .about-hero {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .about-photo {
      width: 140px;
      margin-inline: auto;
    }
  }
</style>
